<P>
327 words 
</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
OFFICER FINED FOR HITTING REDONDO HOUSE WITH TRUCK 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By JANET RAE-DUPREE, TIMES STAFF WRITER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
A Torrance police officer has been placed on probation and ordered to pay a 
$612 fine after he pleaded no contest in South Bay Municipal Court to 
misdemeanor hit-and-run driving for slamming his truck into a Redondo Beach 
house. 
</P>
<P>
Officer Roland Sabara, 34, still faces possible disciplinary action by his own 
department when an internal affairs investigation is completed. 
</P>
<P>
Sgt. Ron Traber, spokesman for the Torrance Police Department, said state law 
prevents officials from revealing what action the department takes. 
</P>
<P>
Municipal Court Judge Sandra Thompson ordered Sabara last Tuesday to pay the 
fine and serve two years of unsupervised probation after Redondo Beach City 
Prosecutor John Slawson submitted a recommendation urging leniency. 
</P>
<P>
"This is a routine hit-and-run with a person who has a perfect DMV history and 
who (pleaded) at the earliest opportunity, without any motions, trial, etc.," 
Slawson wrote in the report. 
</P>
<P>
Sabara, who faced as much as six months in Los Angeles County Jail and a $1,000 
fine, represented himself in court. He could not be reached Wednesday for 
comment. 
</P>
<P>
Sabara was accused of driving his blue 1989 Chevrolet Blazer through a wooden 
fence and into the corner of a house at 615 Diamond St. about 2 a.m. on Aug. 
21. 
</P>
<P>
A witness told police that the driver of the truck backed up and drove off 
without getting out to look at the damage. 
</P>
<P>
Investigating officers found a half-mile trail of fluids that leaked from the 
truck, but the trail dried up before leading them to the vehicle. 
</P>
<P>
The owner of the house, who told police that he slept through the incident, 
found a vanity license plate -- PRFLVSN -- in the debris. It belongs to 
Sabara's truck. 
</P>
<P>
Sabara went to the Redondo Beach Police Department's public counter about 10 
hours after the accident to report his involvement. He said he had fallen 
asleep at the wheel, and reported that he was not under the influence of 
alcohol or drugs at the time of the accident. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA092790-0054 </DOCNO>
<DOCID> 283724 </DOCID>
<DATE>
<P>
September 27, 1990, Thursday, South Bay Edition 
</P>
</DATE>
<SECTION>
<P>
Metro; Part B; Page 4; Column 1 
</P>
</SECTION>
<GRAPHIC>
<P>
Photo, 'Third World' CleanupL:It took five months and a lot of prodding. But a 
group of East Wilmington businessmen saw major progress this week in cleaning 
up the once-cluttered area known as the Third World. Above, a worker contracted 
by the Southern Pacific Railroad for a $1.1-million cleanup of railroad land 
along I and Anaheim streets collects rubbish for removal by Apple Tractor 
Service. "It's a great beginning," said David Stoll, below right, as he and 
fellow businessman Manny Louis oversee the cleanup -- the largest such effort 
to date by a property owner in the area. Previously, the Far East Wilmington 
Improvement Assn. had persuaded the cities of Los Angeles and Long Beach to 
clean up their properties in East Wilmington, said Stoll, a co-chairman of the 
group. Los Angeles police also increased patrols to rid the area of drug 
dealers and prostitutes. Now, Stoll said, the association will try to get the 
Port of Los Angeles to clean up its properties and city agencies to pave area 
streets. "There's still work to be done," Stoll said, "but we're moving." BRIAN 
VANDER BRUG / Los Angeles Times 
</P>
</GRAPHIC>
