BLOCKS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Long Beach officials have decided to challenge the 1990 census count in only 
six blocks of the city, claiming that census takers missed 269 residents. 
</P>
<P>
The limited challenge surprised community workers, who had estimated that up to 
25,000 residents were overlooked. 
</P>
<P>
City officials say the census count came within 0.3% of their estimates. 
However, officials acknowledged that Long Beach lacks the computer and 
record-keeping systems that would enable it to prove whether there was an 
undercount. 
</P>
<P>
Preliminary data showed population in Long Beach, the state's fifth-largest 
city, grew 17% in the last decade to 423,394. 
