<HEADLINE>
<P>
SENATE PANEL OKS SOUTER'S NOMINATION ON A 13-1 VOTE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times Wire Services 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
WASHINGTON 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The Senate Judiciary Committee voted 13 to 1 to approve David Souter's 
nomination to the Supreme Court today, as respect for the New Hampshire 
jurist's intellect outweighed liberal concerns about his views on abortion. 
</P>
<P>
Sen. Edward M. Kennedy (D-Mass.) cast the only vote against Souter. 
</P>
<P>
The full Senate is expected to confirm Souter, probably next week -- shortly 
after the Supreme Court begins its new term. He would become the court's 105th 
jurist and replace Justice William J. Brennan Jr., who retired in July after 34 
years on the court. 
</P>
<P>
Committee Chairman Joseph R. Biden Jr. (D-Del.) joined with six other committee 
Democrats and all six Republicans in supporting Souter. Like many of his 
Democratic colleagues, Biden said he was troubled by uncertainty surrounding 
Souter's positions on rights issues including abortion. 
</P>
<P>
"He's about the best, though, that we're going to be able to do from this 
Administration," he said. 
</P>
<P>
President Bush, in Cleveland to campaign for Republican candidates, said the 
committee vote "is good news for all of us who are committed to the 
Constitution of the United States. He'll be a superb justice for the Supreme 
Court." 
</P>
</TEXT>
